BRUCELLOSIS, CANINE - AUSTRALIA (02): (NEW SOUTH WALES) B. SUIS
***************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

Date: Wed 8 Oct 2014
Source: The Land [edited]
http://www.theland.com.au/news/agriculture/general/news/lls-confirms-brucellosis-in-moree-dogs/2714414.aspx


The North West has had a spate of serious brucellosis infections, with the Local Land Services (LLS) confirming 3 pig hunting dogs have recently tested positive for the _Brucella suis_ strain of the disease, which originates in pigs.

LLS biosecurity and emergencies manager Shaun Slattery said all 3 dogs tested positive for brucellosis following suspected contact with infected feral pigs in the Moree area [northern New South Wales]. "The dogs presented separately to private veterinarians with clinical signs suggestive of brucellosis infection, including fever, vomiting, back pain, blood in urine, lethargy, and enlarged testicles," Dr Slattery said.

Department of Primary Industries (DPI) pigs and poultry senior veterinary officer Amanda Lee said NSW had seen an increase in the number of dogs presenting to vets with suspected brucellosis infection.

"Brucellosis is a serious infectious disease of pigs that can be passed on to other animals and people through contact with urine, blood, saliva, and reproductive materials," Dr Lee said. "The cases we have seen in dogs in NSW have been either as a result of direct contact with an infected feral pig or pig meat, contact with another infected dog, or as a result of the disease being passed on to a pup at birth."

The DPI recommends that dogs infected with brucellosis be euthanased because of the potential risk to people. Anyone who is concerned that their dog may have signs of brucellosis should contact their local veterinarian to have it assessed.

Veterinarians should notify Dr Lee by phone (02) 4640 6308 or email (<amanda.lee@dpi.nsw.gov.au>).

