[According to Australia's annual OIE report for 2013, _Brucella suis_ is a notifiable disease which had been last recorded in domestic animals in 2010 and in wildlife (wild boars) in December 2012. "Animal Health Australia (2010)" reported that _B. suis_ is confined to some populations of feral pigs in Queensland and was detected in a free-range piggery in Queensland in the last quarter of 2010. "The _B. suis_ Accredited Herd Scheme is administered by Biosecurity Queensland on behalf of the industry and currently (2010) has 11 member herds. The scheme aims to ensure piggery freedom from _B. suis_ and to provide a secure source of disease-free breeding stock for pig producers."

_B. suis_ is a public health concern in Australia, being mainly a recreational or occupational disease of feral pig hunters, farm workers, veterinarians, and abattoir workers. According to NSW's Department of Primary Industries (2012), "80 per cent of cases occur in Queensland, with the majority of cases in men aged between 15 and 49 years. Between December 2006 and December 2011, 9 men from NSW were diagnosed with swine brucellosis following regular recreational or occupational feral pig hunting in North West NSW. All men had butchered feral pigs without wearing any protective clothing."

Orchitis is one of the predominant symptoms of _B. suis_ infection in pigs and dogs.

For further background information, please refer to Mod.TG's commentary in archive no 20140628.2571258. - Mod.AS

